80    /**
81    * The UnionTypeBuilder caps the maximum number of alternate types it
82    * remembers and then defaults to "?" (unknown type). By default this max
83    * is 20, but it's very easy for the same property to appear on more than 20
84    * types. Use larger unions for property checking. 3000 was picked
85    * semi-randomly for use by the Google+ FE project.
86    */
87    private static final int PROPERTY_CHECKING_UNION_SIZE = 3000;
88   
89    // TODO(user): An instance of this class should be used during
90    // compilation. We also want to make all types' constructors package private
91    // and force usage of this registry instead. This will allow us to evolve the
92    // types without being tied by an open API.
93   
94    private final transient ErrorReporter reporter;
95   
96    // We use an Array instead of an immutable list because this lookup needs
97    // to be very fast. When it was an immutable list, we were spending 5% of
98    // CPU time on bounds checking inside get().
99    private final JSType[] nativeTypes;
100   
101    private final Map<String, JSType> namesToTypes;
102   
103    // Set of namespaces in which types (or other namespaces) exist.
104    private final Set<String> namespaces = new HashSet<String>();
105   
106    // NOTE(nicksantos): This is a terrible terrible hack. When type expressions
107    // are evaluated, we need to be able to decide whether that type name
108    // resolves to a nullable type or a non-nullable type. Object types are
109    // nullable, but enum types are not.
110    //
111    // Notice that it's not good enough to just declare enum types sooner.
112    // For example, if we have
113    // /** @enum {MyObject} */ var MyEnum = ...;
114    // we won't be to declare "MyEnum" without evaluating the expression
115    // {MyObject}, and following those dependencies starts to lead us into
116    // undecidable territory. Instead, we "pre-declare" enum types and typedefs,
117    // so that the expression resolver can decide whether a given name is
118    // nullable or not.
119    private final Set<String> nonNullableTypeNames = new HashSet<String>();
120   
121    // Types that have been "forward-declared."
122    // If these types are not declared anywhere in the binary, we shouldn't
123    // try to type-check them at all.
124    private final Set<String> forwardDeclaredTypes = new HashSet<String>();
125   
126    // A map of properties to the types on which those properties have been
127    // declared.
128    private final Map<String, UnionTypeBuilder> typesIndexedByProperty =
129    Maps.newHashMap();
130   
131    // A map of properties to each reference type on which those
132    // properties have been declared. Each type has a unique name used
133    // for de-duping.
134    private final Map<String, Map<String, ObjectType>>
135    eachRefTypeIndexedByProperty = Maps.newHashMap();
136   
137    // A map of properties to the greatest subtype on which those properties have

141    Maps.newHashMap();
142

- Uncovered Elements: 0 (0) Complexity: 0 Complexity Density: -
167    public static enum ResolveMode {
168    /**
169    * Expressions are converted into Unknown blobs that can be
170    * resolved into complex types.
171    */
172    LAZY_EXPRESSIONS,
173   
174    /**
175    * Expressions are evaluated. If any names in the expression point to
176    * unknown types, then we create a proxy {@code NamedType} structure
177    * until the type can be resolved.
178    *
179    * This is the legacy way of resolving ways, and may not exist in the
180    * future.
181    */
182    LAZY_NAMES,
183   
184    /**
185    * Expressions and type names are evaluated aggressively. A warning
186    * will be emitted if a type name fails to resolve to a real type.
187    */
188    IMMEDIATE
189    }
190   
191    private ResolveMode resolveMode = ResolveMode.LAZY_NAMES;
